opinions.missing_from_js:
The JavaScript ecosystem has broadend far too much. There are far to many ways of achieving things. As a result one often does things just as they are done in that blog post or that YouTube video, without asking why it is done that way and without questioning why it is done this way. The fact that new frameworks, libraries, language features, and even new transpiled languages appear almost daily does not ease those issues.
It is time for consolidation, time for improving what is there, instead of letting the ecosystem diverge forever. This does not mean that there should be for every use case but one way to go. But we as a comunity should ask ourselves whether it is helpful to create something new anytime we encounter a flaw in something already existing. Would it not be more effective to collectively improve what is there?

opinions.missing_from_js: Not so much what's missing in JavaScript as a language, but just the overall experience of doing frontend work. Anyone doing .NET development has been using Visual Studio for over a decade. Anyone doing Java development has been using Eclipse/IntelliJ/NetBeans for over a decade. It's a stable environment. But the tools we use when doing frontend development are constantly changing and we are still far away from a definitive ecosystem. Whether it's tooling (grunt, gulp, webpack) or a shift from the web in general (HTTP/2, Web Assembly, security vulnerabilities, OAuth), there are so many influences on how we should be going about stuff. It is tiring.
